Foundation of Amank’Sha<br>
<br>
Chapter 1: Into the Eye of the Storm<br>
<br>
Ca’reem knelt before the lake.  Her daughter, Ahr’il, is now fifteen, but is showing much more maturity than most of her age.<br>
<br>
“Mother, tell me again of your dreams.”<br>
<br>
“Arh’il, you will soon find that your dreams are much more than they appear, if you only look deep insie yourself.”<br>
<br>
“Mother, please.  Tell me of the future.”<br>
<br>
Ca’reem hated to speak of what was to come, for she knew that she had to hide much of what she knew.  Her own death was comming, and she would die by the same hands that killed her mother.  But her own death didn’t bother her.  She knew it was to come, and she would go willingly.  All that mattered was the survival of Ahr’il.<br>
<br>
“Arh’il, I will tell you once again.  This lake, with the tiny stone island in the center, is always there.  As are the five stone pillars that surround us.  A secong great people will come, and by our will, we will makew peace with them.  But there are spies among us, and they know of my dreams as well.  But in these dreams, Ahr’il, you are the hero.  You are the one who will grow up to punish those who killed your mother before me.  You will rise up in arms, and you will bring to them the full will of Ramm’Tiel.  And then, when the island we stand on, this island, Kroon, falls into the sea, you will be the one to bring our people to a new land.  There will be many new adventures.  Glowing white light will move your sould to hundreds of new worlds, and our race will prosper once again.”<br>
<br>
Arh’il sat patiently, watching her mother tell the tale.  She had seen some things like this when she meditated, but all too often she could not remember enough to tell her mother.<br>
<br>
Outside of the mile-wide circle of the five stones and the great lake, storms raged violently.  Hail, lightning, rain, and blinding sea spray welcomed anyone willing to venture out to die in their midst.<br>
<br>
“Mother, what of the rest of the island.  What is happening to Kroon?”<br>
<br>
Ca’reem filled a large, shallow bowl with watter from the lake.  Several drops of oil went in, and the clear water swirled with color, forming a shape of the island itself.<br>
<br>
“Kroon is going through a change.  You se, the island is ten miles wide, and several thousand feet above the water.  But it is suspended by a huge pillar in the center, and that pillar is wearing away.  Mind you, young one, that there is no fear here in the center of the island, the stones protect us.  There is magic here Arh’il, more than that I have ever felt.  More than what I knew when I was near your mother before me.  There are things here that belong to us, to Ramm’Tiel, but there are things that belong to others.<br>
<br>
“Like the columns, mother?”<br>
<br>
“Well, yes, like the columns.  You have grown very wise, Arh’il, and I fear that you will surpass my talent by a great deal when you venture out on your own.”<br>
<br>
“Mother, I want to learn the things you know.  I want to use the water to make shapes, I want to see as far as my mind will go.”<br>
<br>
“This will all come with time, young Rhakk.  What would you do if you could do as I?”<br>
<br>
“I would make the storm go away.  It has kept the sun away for so long.  How long has it been since the crops have grown?”<br>
<br>
“It has been several weeks.  Soon, we will be out of food.  But the water will keep us alive.  And the sun will return very soon.”<br>
<br>
“I could make it go away.  I could make all the storms elave us alone forever.”<br>
<br>
“Indeed, you will.  But you may not like the power you recieve.”<br>
<br>
At this, Ahr’il bowed her head, and thought of the things her mother had said.  She was very wise, and Ahr’il knew that what she said was true, but she felt that there was an emptiness that came with her story.  There was something of grief that her mother felt when she told it tonite, something that she felt would plauge her when her story came true.  But there was no time to dwell on her own idle thoughts, she had to meditate more, so that she would be more like her mother.<br>
<br>
Ca'reem left, leaving Ahr'il to her own thoughts, and Ca'reem hoped that her daughter would learn quickly to dream and summon spirits, to call upon Ramm'Tiel, and to do more than Ca'reem herself would be able to do.  But she knew that it would take many years for anything to become of her daughters dreams.  She knew that there was no Rhakk alive that had powers so great at so young.  Yet then again, Ahr'il had sown more progress than expected.  She loved to meditate every day, and did so more than Ca'reem had the will to do.<br>
<br>
&quot;She has great patience, doesn't she Ca'reem,&quot; said another Rhakk from besider her.  Ca'reem looked back at her daughter, still kneeling by the shore.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes she does.  More patience than I.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;More patience than all of us.  Ca'reem, Ahr'il will lead us all one day, wont she.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ma'nuk, you know that I will not speak of the future.  I am uncertain of t myself.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You lie.  You know exactly what is to become of her dont you?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You speak in tounges like that, and you are liable to find yourself in the storm on your own.  You know why I fled here?  It is because the Yomen banished my mother for seeing the future.  And yet it is because they saw the future themselves that they forced our people to slavery.  It is the future that is tainted.  No one is for sure of what events will start the chain, or what will end it.  But it is for sure that your future will bee one of great dispair if you do not hold your tounge more carefully, Ma'nuk.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I am once again made unworthy of your knowlege, Ca'reem.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Dont inult yourself, Ma'nuk.  Ignorance led to the destruction of our people, and it is ignorance and simple laws that made our people blind.  But it will be our time once again, for we can see on this island.  We can see farther then those of Rhaksha.  We can feel things they cannot, and we are the ones who have escaped slavery.  And though we are few, our powers are greater than that of any Rhaksha.  We are the treu Rhakk, Ma'nuk, do not forget this.  We will be the ones who make it when the storm reaches out its tendrils to lands unknown.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;May the water bless your will Ca'reem,&quot; Ma'nuk said, as he bowed, &quot;And the sea be your guide.&quot;<br>
<br>
Ma'nuk walked away, and Ca'reem went her way as well, but both would end up close together, in makeshift huts and small, animal-like dens in the earth.  But it would not be like that forever, for Ca'reem knew one thing above all else, that few others grasped:<br>
<br>
Water changed things.  Though many years it could take, water was that of one to wait, and to slowly erode the forces that kept it contained, and not even solid rock could stand in its way.<br>
