&quot;She still sits there Ca'reem.  Do you ever wonder what she is thinking?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;It is not my place to ask her.  She will tell me what she wishes.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Are you not afraid that she will fall into a comma?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I trust her skills, she has the blood of my mother in her.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;She had no care about the consiquences.  She sacrificed her life willignly&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;As will I, if the time ever comes that I must give my life for Ahr'il.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But we are safe here, there is no need to worry of that.  You dont wish to upset the colonists.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But if I do not, I fear that ignorance will once again shatter our lives, as it did those before us.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;There is no need to worry Ca'reem here we are safe.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I hope you are right Ma'nuk.&quot;<br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
Ahr'il had vivid dreams.  Colors swirled into shapes, and shapes into living forms.  She saw the water erode the rocks from the shore, yet she saw other images.  She saw tiny bits of rock with water flowing inside of them, making runes appear on the outside.  She saw Rhakk disapear from sight, and watched as others were killed by strange brown creatures.<br>
<br>
There were other things, as she felt herself near the stages beyond her limits.  But she pressed further, deeper within her own soul.  She knew she was not ready to be as far inside as she was, but she had to move on.  She cast wards to keep the demons away, and pressed further.<br>
<br>
She was suddenly swallowed in blue light.  There was a larger soul there, something that enveloped her completely.  She felt that it was kind, but angered by something.<br>
<br>
It seemed to suffocate her, but she was entranced by it.  It was warm, and made her feel a power surge through her body.  Her mother never said anything of dreams like this.  The blue was taking over her soul.<br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
A rush of water was heard from the small hut that Ca'reem slept quietly in.  Somehting disturbed her sleep, some kind of power, being drawn from the water around her.  This disturbance was so great that it awoke Ca'reem from a deep sleep.  Something was happening at the lake.  Someone was summoning the great sprit of Ramm'Tiel!<br>
<br>
Ca'reem burst from the hut, and ran toward the lake.  There she saw a sight that both amazed and horrified her at the same time.  Ahr'il was suspended in the air, columns of water being pulled from the lake and enveloping Ahr'il, lifting her from the ground like tentacles of an octopus.  They pulled her until she was hovering twenty feet over the small rocky island in the center of the lake.  The watery columns lifeted outward, until they disconected themselves from the lake, and moved at their own will, yet still connected to Ahr'il.  Four of them dropped back to the water with a deafaning crash of sea spray, leaving five of them whirling in the air.<br>
<br>
Colonists began to wake fromtheir slumber and run out to the lake, unable to do anything to stop what was happening.<br>
<br>
Ca'reem watched in horror as her daughter was overcome by the spirit, too young to control it's power.  She would die soon, if she did not awaken herself...<br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
The blue light began to focus itself into tight beams, and bubled up around her body.  The tendrils moved at their own will, and Ahr'il began to have a harder time breathing.<br>
<br>
But she would not abbandon such progress.  Thrusting her arms out, she began to chant invocations to control the light, but none prevailed.  White light hit her, in the form of four tight beams.  A sudden surge of power overcame her, and she could breathe again.  The blue columns thrust outward, and seemed to unlock even more magical power.<br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
The serpentine columns of water suddenly began to straighten, and then spin around Ahr'il.  The nearly fifty foot rock columns that surrounded the lake began to glow with a feverent white light, brining the entire camp to the look of broad daylight although it was night.<br>
<br>
Outside, the storm began to scream and his with ear-splitting noises, and the winds kicked up dramatically.  A veritable hurricane centered on the island, the gigantic storm released lightning into the skies in all directions...<br>
<br>
But the stones took this power from the sky, and used it to fuel their own.  Ca'reem felt completely surrounded by a thick air of magic, as though she were swimmin in deep mud.  It was hard to breathe in, but she felt herself suddenly at complete peace, and knew what was happening.<br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
Ahr'il had no conrtol over her actions as she uttered spells that she had no knowlege of.  Her surroundings turned completely white, and she soon found herself lying on the floor, in utter virtigo.  A blue ball of light hovered above her.<br>
<br>
&quot;Do not be afraid,&quot; it spoke in a voice that echoed of a chourus, filled with only soprano and bass notes, &quot;I am the one that your people worship.  I was sent with those that first landed here, from powers greater than I.  I am the one who gave your people your powers.  I am the one who determined what you would look like and how you would act as a culture.  But even I cannot see the future as I would like it to be.  Your people ignored my blessing, your mother's bloodline.  They shunned her, and your people collapsed.  That is not my fault.  I cannot control you people completely.  But there are more like I, and you have found the secret that was placed in this land by those who created I.  Thus I am the one who can bring your people no further.  I can only act as your guide, and marvel at the powers you posess.  Your bloodline will be the one to bring together the lands, and your people will find that there is a greater purpose, but even I know not what it is.  I am only the key to the door.&quot;<br>
<br>
With that, the light exploded in a violent rage, sucking Ahr'il back into the blue essince that was her god, and she released the full power of Ramm'Tiel.<br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
Ca'reem was forced back from were she stood, pushed slowly throught the thickness of the pure magic around her.  An explosive beam of light shot from her daughter ut into the sky, and the storm exploded outwards, showing the night stars once again.  Ahr'il dropped to the ground as if she were no more than a mere puppet, and the small island she lay on turned from brown to black, and grew twice in size, so that twenty people could stand on i if they were cramped together.<br>
<br>
With no boats available, Ca'reem was in a panic.  Her daughter had been overcome by the poer of her god, and now she laid dead on a tiny stone island.  Ca'reem ran up to the edge of the lake, and peered out at her daughter.  Slowly, in a frail manner, Ahr'il began to move...<br>
